            "last_activity_date": 1434711368,
            "creation_date": 1434711368,
            "body": "<p>From a bit of research I realised that it is hard to do a foolproof one for all the possible URLs. <a href=\"https://mathiasbynens.be/demo/url-regex\" rel=\"nofollow\">This website<\/a> has regex which matches many website URLs. What you can do is use the complement of that regex.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 30936396,
            "question_id": 30936131
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/KHhzd.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 3438751,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3297613,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3297613/avinash-raj",
                "reputation": 175294,
                "display_name": "Avinash Raj",
                "accept_rate": 74
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1434713495,
            "creation_date": 1434713495,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p>@AvinashRaj I have put the regex in negative lookahead but that seems not to be working <code>^(?!.*/(?:(https?:\\/\\/)|\\1?www\\.)\\w+\\.\\w{2,5}/).*<\/code><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>You just need to remove the regex delimiters.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>^(?!.*(?:(https?:\\/\\/)|\\1?www\\.)\\w+\\.\\w{2,5}).*\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://regex101.com/r/rR3uK6/1\" rel=\"nofollow\">DEMO<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 30937084,
            "question_id": 30936131
        }
